ABBREVIATIONS

 

 

In this catalogue the instruments (setting) are enumerated with the abbreviation of their Italian term in the sequence usually applied in the score. The number of wind instruments is indicated by two groups of figures. Thus 3, 3, 3, 3 4, 3, 3, 1 means a force of 3 flutes, 3 oboes, 3 clarinets and 3 bassons as well as 4 horns, 3 trumpets, 3 trombones and 1 tuba.

 

Other abbreviations :

a. alto

b. bass

bar. baritone

batt. percussion

cb. double bass

cel. celeste

cemb. harpsichord

cfg. double bassoon

chit. guitar

c.i. English horn

cl.                               clarinet

cor. horn

es(s). performer(s)

fg. bassoon

mand. mandolin

org. organ

pf. piano

picc. piccolo

s.                                soprano

sass. saxophone

t.                                 tenor

timp. timpani

tr. trumpet

trb. trombone

vl. violin

vla viola

vlc. violoncello

xyl. xylophone

zimb. ungh. cimbalom

 

All other instrumental names are given in full, or are self-explanatory combinations of the above abbreviations.

 

Doublings are indicated in brackets thus :

 

3 (c.i.) signifies that the 3rd oboe doubles English horn,

3 (III=c.i.) signifies that instead of the 3rd oboe English horn plays all through.

 

The miscellaneous percussion instruments are included in batt.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

HUNGARIAN PRONUNCIATION

 

 

The Hungarian Alphabet

Vowel Explanation of pronunciation

 

a short (hot, what)

long (French : ah)

e short (get, met)

long (day, name)

i short (lip, is)

long (he, tea)

o short (politics)

long (hole, coat)

short (French : le, ne)

u short (good, put)

long (French : jour)

short (French : tu)

b short

d short

l short
